questions.text: What type of organism did the exposure come from?
Does the patient have evidence of significant pain, swelling or blistering at or around the site of the bite or sting?
Does the patient have evidence of local tissue damage or necrosis at or around the site of the bite or sting?
Does the patient have evidence of a direct specific cardio toxin effect?

Does the patient have evidence of paralytic neurological system effects (one or more of:  flaccid paralysis, ptosis, dysarthria, dysphagia, fixed dilated pupils, pinpoint pupils, partial or complete ophthalmoplegia, limb weakness, diminished/absent deep tendon reflexes, respiratory paralysis, impaired gait, ataxia)?
Does the patient have evidence of dysfunction of the haemostatic system (one or more of: consumptive coagulopathy, DIC, anticoagulant coagulopathy, increased bleeding, thromboses or emboli)?
Does the patient have evidence of direct venom spit, into the eyes or adjacent areas, as a result of an encounter with a venomous animal able to spit venom, such as a spitting cobra?

Does the patient have evidence of general non-specific systemic effects such as headache, nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, diarrhoea, tachypnoea, respiratory distress, hypotension, dizziness, collapse, convulsions etc?

Does the patient have evidence of an anterior pituitary haemorrhage, related to an episode of envenoming (such as by a Russellâ€™s viper etc) or other toxin-induced cause? (evidence may include imaging of the anterior pituitary, or the various systemic effects following major damage to the anterior pituitary, because of hypopituitarism, similar to Sheehan's syndrome)
Does the patient have evidence of non-paralytic neuroexcitatory effects (sympathetic or parasympathetic system activation, catecholamine storm-like effects etc)?

Does the patient have evidence of genitourinary system effects including acute kidney injury (one or more of: polyuria, oliguria, anuria, elevated blood creatinine and/or urea) , renal pain, renal tenderness, bladder distension, urinary retention?
Does the patient have evidence of systemic or local rhabdomyolysis (one or more of: gross elevation of plasma CK, >1500IU/l, myoglobinuria etc)?
Does the patient have evidence of primary cardiovascular system effects (one or more of: tachycardia, bradycardia, hypertension, hypotension, cardiac arrhythmia, cardiac failure, shock)?
Does the patient have evidence of effects on red blood cells such as anaemia, haemolysis etc?
Does the patient have evidence of dermatologic effects (one or more of: dermatitis, contact dermatitis, urticaria, rash, erythromelagia)?

Does the patient have evidence of non-paralytic respiratory system effects (one or more of tachypnoea, reduced PaO2, hypoxia, cyanosis, dyspnoea, respiratory distress, pulmonary oedema, respiratory failure)?
Does the patient have evidence of effects on platelets such as thrombocytopenia?
Does the patient have evidence of effects on white blood cells such as leukocytosis, leukopenia, lymphopenia etc?
Does the patient have evidence of allergy or immune system effects (such as one or more of: anaphylaxis, angio-oedema, allergic rash etc)?
Does the patient have evidence of other effects not covered elsewhere, such as priapism, metallic taste in the mouth, bladder distension?
Does the patient have evidence of gastrointestinal system effects (one or more of: nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, abdominal pain)?
Does the patient have evidence of other non-paralytic or non-neuroexcitatory effects such as decreased conscious state, unconsciousness, seizures, amnesia, confusion, visual disturbances etc?
Does the patient have evidence of hepatic damage, dysfunction or failure?
Does the patient have evidence of direct effects in the mouth/throat such as pain, swelling, blistering etc, after oral ingestion of the organism (particularly some plants)?

Does the patient have evidence of musculoskeletal system effects (one or more of: muscle pain, muscle tenderness, myoclonus, muscle swelling, joint pain, joint swelling, joint limitation of movement)?
Has the patient experienced hallucinations as a symptom of this toxin exposure?
Does the patient have evidence of primary metabolic system effects, such as hypoglycaemia, procalcitonaemia, acidosis, alkalosis etc?
Does the patient have purple coloured urine?
Does the patient have pre-existing kidney dysfunction/failure?

values: trichyurus , caffer , gracilloides , pallidus , parvus , werneri , whitei
new guinea and south pacific islands
